=EN>Morkenlar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Councilman</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(5/23/02 2:39:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/finfinitusvindicatfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The War of Northern Agression (aka Civil War)</span><hr size=1> Women couldn't vote either, Fest.  So does that mean every decision made by the US government was illegitimate until womens suffrage?  No one under 18 can vote - does that mean every decision made by our government wasn't democratic?<br><br>The same arguement can be applied to the Revolutionary War, by the way.  Women didn't get to vote . . . they had no say in the matter, so that wasn't democracy either.<br><br>So if you argue that the Southern States seceding wasn't a democratic decision, because black people weren't allowed to vote on it, then I respond that the Declaration of Independence wasn't either, because women couldn't vote on that.<br><br>All democracies have restrictions, for whatever reasons (some good, some not) on who can vote.  Historically, these have usually been age, race, sex, wealth, and in some nations religion.  This doesn't eliminate the fact that decisions voted on WERE voted on democratically.  <br><br>I'm not defending slavery, because I don't think slavery is right, never have.  BUT, and here's the catch - the Federal Government wasn't taking any action to eliminate slavery - that came about as a tactic to disrupt the Southern economy (if you can call it that) and lifestyle, and frankly worked pretty well to do so.  Smart strategic and PR move.<br><br>The Federal Govenment did not go to war to tell the southern states they had to free their slaves - it went to war to force the Southern States to stay in the Union.  It wasn't about slavery, it was about whether or not individual states had the right to dissolve their membership in the United States of America. <p></br><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~shay01/morksiggy.gif></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/ufesteringwounds.showPublicProfile?language=EN>FesteringWounds</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(5/23/02 2:49:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/finfinitusvindicatfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The War of Northern Agression (aka Civil War)</span><hr size=1> /nod <br><br>i agree that the north's decision was not a selfless act.  <br><br>i only countered your statement about the &quot; &quot; remark about the desire to secede was a unanimous decision. <p><img src="http://home.triad.rr.com/apassmore/sig3.jpg"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666699><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/ulachlann.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lachlann</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(5/23/02 3:26:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/finfinitusvindicatfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bonq.net/~lachlann/ivicon_copy.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The War of Northern Agression (aka Civil War)</span><hr size=1> &quot;A People's History of the United States:  1492 to present&quot; by Howard Zinn .. its really interesting reading, and while not trying to get off topic, you'll learn a LOT about the Civil War in it.  Stuff you don't learn in school.  It does require you to have a working knowledge of history though, and not that garbage you lear