d rich people how can we be an accurate representation of the people. You cant get elected to office unless you have money to run a campaign. Once a person is voted into office they run the government by cronyism. <br><br>Every president we have had has been separated from the people they govern by a generation, and sometimes by 2 genrations. When we have people in charge of us who are making descision based on ideas and beliefs that dont coincide with the current change of the nation, we are doomed to forever be behind the power curve.<br><br>So yes, the civil war was a farce upon the government, but nothing as bad as it has become lately. <p><a href=mailto:Dandaelus@allakhazam.com>Dandaelus Wyldheart</a><br>57th Outrider<br>EPIC ENHANCED <br>Infinitus Vindicat<br>Prexus<br><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=24243>Veiw Me Here</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666699><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/umorkenlar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Morkenlar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Councilman</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(5/23/02 5:49:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/finfinitusvindicatfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The War of Northern Agression (aka Civil War)</span><hr size=1> Actually, Dandy, the electoral system (this includes congress, not just the electoral college) wasn't a farce at all.  It was (and is) a necesary medium.  Unless you care to argue that we could assemble everyone for a vote on issues in the late 1700s?  <br><br>You simply couldn't do a public vote on issues then, because people weren't capable of traveling to do so, they weren't educated (you want a large population that can't read making laws?), and weren't knowledgable about the complexities of govenment, economics, foreign relations, etc.<br><br>Hell, I don't think you could do a RELIABLE public vote on issues now, even with computers.  It wouldn't take but maybe a dozen key people in whatever system you set up cooperating, and they could corrupt the entire system.  A couple programmers, network engineers, security specialists, and maybe a statician to make sure the numbers don't look too off to get caught, and they would rule the nation forever.<br><br>The electoral vote doesn't take away freedom.  Yes, its been abused a few times in the past when the electoral college didn't vote as the people directed, but its all our fault for allowing that.  Not doing so should be a criminal offense of a major magnitude, but it isn't, so people apparently don't think it was wrong enough to warrant a change.  As the old saying goes, every country has the government it deserves.<br><br>Have to have money to get elected?  Nope.  You just have to be in one of the two political parties, they supply the cash for campaigns.  Sure, extra money helps, but if thats all it took, Perot would have won a few years ago.<br><br>Cronyism?  Now you complain of politicians putting people they know in positions of power?  You'd rather they pull someone off the street, in whom they have no trust or knowledge of the person's abilities, to run the govenment?  <br><br>Presidents have to be, what, 35 or 40 years old?  Something like that, anyway.  Whats the objection here?  You want someone that has less experience with the world in power?  Sorry, age doesn't make everyone wiser, but it does make most people wiser, and I'll settle for that for now. <p></br><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~shay01/morksiggy.gif></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/ufesteringwounds.showPublicProfile?language=EN>FesteringWounds</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(5/23/02 5:58:13 pm)</font><br>